    <title>Combined summary - Covenant opcode proposal OP_CONSTRAINDESTINATION (an alternative to OP_CTV)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T00:26:00.089848+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-July/019287.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In recent Bitcoin development mailing lists, discussions among developers have revolved around proposals to improve the security of wallet vaults. One proposed solution involves using an opcode called OP_CD to create highly secure wallets that allow normal people to hold self-custody of their keys without fear of loss or theft and without the hassle of safe deposit boxes. The proposal suggests limiting the amount that can be sent from an address in a wallet vault by combining coins into a single output and encumbering it with a script that allows limited amounts to be sent to a destination address while requiring all other bitcoins to be returned to the sender in a new change output. Another proposal suggests implementing a way to limit the maximum amount to be sent from an address in wallet vaults to thwart theft where all funds are swept in a single transaction. The discussion also involves finding ways to optimize Bitcoin transactions and reduce their size. One proposal suggests allowing the omission of an output value in cases where the entire output amount is contributed by that input. This would only make the transaction about 7% larger and would reduce the overhead of specifying output amounts to 2 bytes for most outputs. Another topic discussed was the potential for miners to manipulate fee rates in Bitcoin transactions and its impact on the network. One proposed solution involves constraining the amount of fee an output is allowed to contribute using a median fee-rate per block and a maximum fee contribution limit. However, concerns were raised about the mechanism's manipulability by miners and the need for alternative mechanisms such as mutual spend clauses and fee overrides. Furthermore, there were discussions about covenant opcodes like OP_CD and their benefits compared to traditional multisig wallets. Billy Tetrud explained that it allows for highly secure wallet vaults with better redundancy than traditional multisig wallets. There were also proposals to split up the fee-limiting functionality from OP_CD into a separate opcode called OP_LIMITFEECONTRIBUTION and to evaluate what addresses an input goes to without knowing what amounts it contributes to each output. Finally, proposals were made to implement mechanisms for limiting the maximum amount that can be sent from an address using a combination of parameters, including a minimum value imposed on the percentage and a transaction frequency expressed as a number of blocks before a next transaction can be sent from the encumbered address(es). These proposals could alleviate privacy concerns since the wallet would be able to mix outputs.</summary>
